<SPAN CLASS="smallcaps">Dediticii</SPAN>
		</A>
in Smith's <I>Dictionary of Greek and Roman Antiquities</I>.
	</DIV>


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note53" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref53
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">53</A>
	<A HREF="
https://www.hs-augsburg.de/~harsch/Chronologia/Lsante01/Vergilius/ver_ae01.html
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(EClickHere+'Book 1<BR>of Vergil\'s <I>Aeneid</I>'+Lat2+LatSearch+'togatam</SPAN>',WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Verg. <I>Aen.</I> 1.282</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note54" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref54
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">54</A>
<SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">Congiarium</SPAN>, strictly a distribution of oil (from <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">congius</SPAN>, a <SPAN CLASS="whole">liquid</SPAN> measure) came to be used of any largess.

	<DIV CLASS="mynoteWide">
		<P CLASS="b0 a0 justify">
Thayer's Note: For comprehensive details and sources, see the article
		<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/secondary/SMIGRA*/Congiarium.html
		"TARGET="princeps"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Smith1,WIDTH,SmithWidth1)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
<SPAN CLASS="smallcaps">Congiarium</SPAN>
		</A>
in Smith's <I>Dictionary of Greek and Roman Antiquities</I>.
	</DIV>


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note55" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref55
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">55</A>
The <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">tesserae nummulariae</SPAN> were small tablets or round hollow balls of wood, marked with numbers. They were distributed to the people instead of money and entitled the holder to receive the sum inscribed upon them. Grain, oil,


<A ID="p189x"></A><SPAN CLASS="pagenum">(p189)</SPAN>and various commodities were distributed by similar <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">tesserae</SPAN>; <I>cf.</I> <A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#40.2
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,5,WIDTH,140)"
onMouseOut="nd();">chap. xl.2</A>;
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Nero*.html#11.2.2
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
<I>Nero</I>, xi</A>;
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Domitian*.html#4.5.2
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
<I>Dom.</I> iv</A>.

	<DIV CLASS="mynoteWide">
		<P CLASS="b0 a0 justify">
Thayer's Note: For comprehensive details and sources, see the article
		<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/secondary/SMIGRA*/Tessera.html#token
		"TARGET="princeps"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Smith1,WIDTH,SmithWidth1)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
<SPAN CLASS="smallcaps">Tessera</SPAN>
		</A>
in Smith's <I>Dictionary of Greek and Roman Antiquities</I>.
	</DIV>


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note56" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref56
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">56</A>
<I>Cf.</I> <A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Julius*.html#39
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><I>Jul.</I> xxxix.1</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note57" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref57
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">57</A>
<I>Cf.</I> <A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Julius*.html#39.2.3
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><I>Jul.</I> xxxix.2</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note58" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref58
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">58</A>
The auditorium was divided horizontally into three parts: <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">ima</SPAN> (<SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">prima</SPAN>), <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">media</SPAN>, and <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">summa</SPAN> (<SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">ultima</SPAN>) <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">cavea</SPAN>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note59" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref59
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">59</A>
This puzzling statement is thus explained by Baum.-Crusius: "<I>i.e.</I> ex aedibus proxime adjacentibus, unde prospectus erat in Circum. Coenacula autem in summis aedibus esse solebant. Idem narrat
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Cassius_Dio/57*.html#11
	"TARGET="Cassius_Dio_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Dio,WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Dio 57.11
	</A> de Tiberio: <SPAN LANG="el" CLASS="Greek">τοὺς τῶν ἵππων ἀγῶνας ἐξ οἰκίας καὶ αὐτὸς τῶν ἀπελευθέρων τινὸς πολλάκις ἑώρα</SPAN>."


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note60" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref60
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">60</A>
<SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">Pulvinar</SPAN> was originally a sacred couch for a god. The honour was given to Julius Caesar (see
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Julius*.html#76
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
<I>Jul.</I> lxxvi.1</A>) and the term was later applied, as here, to the place reserved for the emperor and his family; <I>cf.</I> <A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Claudius*.html#4.3.2
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><I>Claud.</I> iv.3</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note61" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref61
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">61</A>
That is, given at Rome in the Greek language and dress. Or <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">Graeco certamini</SPAN> may mean "a contest in Greece."


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note62" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref62
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">62</A>
Those of
	<A HREF="
E/Gazetteer/Places/Europe/Italy/Lazio/Roma/Rome/_Texts/PLATOP*/Theatrum_Pompei.html
	"TARGET="princeps"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Platner1,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Pompey</A>,
	<A HREF="
E/Gazetteer/Places/Europe/Italy/Lazio/Roma/Rome/_Texts/PLATOP*/Theatrum_Balbi.html
	"TARGET="princeps"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Platner1,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Balbus</A>, and
	<A HREF="
E/Gazetteer/Places/Europe/Italy/Lazio/Roma/Rome/_Texts/PLATOP*/Theatrum_Marcelli.html
	"TARGET="princeps"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Platner1,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Marcellus</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note63" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref63
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">63</A>
That is, his middle finger, <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">infamis digitus</SPAN>; it implied a charge of obscenity; <I>cf.</I> <A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Caligula*.html#56.2.2
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><I>Calig.</I> lvi.2</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note64" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref64
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">64</A>
That is, appointed them to the offices of <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">tribunus cohortis</SPAN>, <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">praefectus alae</SPAN>, and <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">tribunus legionis</SPAN>, usually open only to knights.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note65" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref65
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">65</A>
A limited <SPAN CLASS="whole">citizen</SPAN>&shy;ship, taking its name from the old Latin cities and varying in different cases and at different times.

	<DIV CLASS="mynoteWide">
		<P CLASS="b0 a0 justify">
Thayer's Note: For comprehensive details and sources, see the article
		<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/secondary/SMIGRA*/Latinitas.html
		"TARGET="princeps"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Smith1,WIDTH,SmithWidth1)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
<SPAN CLASS="smallcaps">Latinitas</SPAN>
		</A>
in Smith's <I>Dictionary of Greek and Roman Antiquities</I>.
	</DIV>


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note66" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref66
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">66</A>
<SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">Diploma</SPAN>, strictly any document written on a <SPAN CLASS="whole">two-leaved</SPAN> tablet, is used specially of those which secured to travellers the use of the public post (see
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#49.3
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,5,WIDTH,140)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
chap. xlix.3</A>) and other privileges; <I>cf.</I> <A HREF="
http://www.thelatinlibrary.com/cicero/fam6.shtml#12
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(EClickHere+'Cicero\'s Epistulae<BR>ad Familiares to that letter'+Lat2+LatSearch+'Diploma</SPAN>.<BR>')"
onMouseOut="nd();">Cic. <I>Ad Fam.</I> 6.12</A>.

	<DIV CLASS="mynoteWide">
		<P CLASS="b0 a0 justify">
Thayer's Note: For details and sources, see the article
		<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/secondary/SMIGRA*/Diploma.html
		"TARGET="princeps"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Smith1,WIDTH,SmithWidth1)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
<SPAN CLASS="smallcaps">Diploma</SPAN>
		</A>
in Smith's <I>Dictionary of Greek and Roman Antiquities</I>.
	</DIV>


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note67" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref67
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">67</A>
<SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">Dominus</SPAN>, "master," in the time of the Republic indicated the relation between master and slaves. Tiberius also shrank from it
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Tiberius*.html#27.1.3
	"TARGET="Suetonius_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EPlusL,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(<I>Tib.</I> xxvii)</A>, and it was first adopted by Caligula and Domitian. From the time of Trajan it was usual in the sense of "Lord" or "Sire."


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note68" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref68
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">68</A>
That is, they did not make a morning call on him, as in other days.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note69" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref69
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">69</A>
See
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#35
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,5,WIDTH,140)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
chap. xxxv.1</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note70" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref70
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">70</A>
The Romans in their wills often express the opinion freely about public men and affairs; <I>cf.</I> <A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#66.4.2
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,5,WIDTH,140)"
onMouseOut="nd();">chap. lxvi</A>, and
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Cassius_Dio/58*.html#25
	"TARGET="Cassius_Dio_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Dio,WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Cassius Dio, 58.25</A>, where it is said that Fulcinius Tiro, who died in prison, bitterly assailed Tiberius in his will.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note71" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref71
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">71</A>
The movable seats provided for the advocates, witnesses, etc.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note72" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref72
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">72</A>
The custom of defending an accused person by a general eulogy of his character was forbidden by Pompey in his third <SPAN CLASS="whole">consul</SPAN>&shy;ship
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Cassius_Dio/40*.html#52
	"TARGET="Cassius_Dio_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Dio,WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(Dio, 40.52)</A>, but was nevertheless resorted to, even by Pompey himself
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Cassius_Dio/40*.html#55
	"TARGET="Cassius_Dio_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Dio,WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(Dio, 40.55)</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note73" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref73
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">73</A>
September 22 and 23.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note74" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref74
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">74</A>
Probably of the scribes and other minor officials.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note75" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref75
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">75</A>
One's tutelary divinity, or familiar spirit, closely identified with the person himself.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note76" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref76
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">76</A>
The form of purchase consisted in thrice touching a balance (<SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">libra</SPAN>) with a penny (<SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">as</SPAN>), in the presence of the praetor.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note77" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref77
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">77</A>
A record of the events of the imperial household. The custom of keeping such a day-book apparently dated from the time of Augustus. See Friedländer, <I>Roman Life and Manners</I> (Eng. Trans.), IV, p56.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note78" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref78
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">78</A>
The host usually occupied the <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">summus locus</SPAN> on the <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">imus lectus</SPAN>.

	<DIV CLASS="mynote">
		<P CLASS="b0 a0 justify">
Thayer's Note: Stripped of its Latin, that's the uppermost position (of three) on the couch called "lowest". For details and sources on Roman dining etiquette, with diagrams, see the article
		<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/secondary/SMIGRA*/Triclinium.html
		"TARGET="princeps"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Smith1,WIDTH,SmithWidth1)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
<SPAN CLASS="smallcaps">Triclinium</SPAN>
		</A>
in Smith's <I>Dictionary of Greek and Roman Antiquities</I>.
	</DIV>


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note79" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref79
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">79</A>
Ancient divisions of the citizens for political purposes. In cases of adoption the <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">curiae</SPAN> were represented by thirty


<A ID="p221x"></A><SPAN CLASS="pagenum">(p221)</SPAN>lictors, presided over by the pontifex maximus. This form of adoption was usual with adults; <I>cf.</I> <A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#64
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,5,WIDTH,140)"
onMouseOut="nd();">chap. lxiv.1</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note80" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref80
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">80</A>
Pandataria.

	<DIV CLASS="mynote">
		<P CLASS="b0 a0 justify">
Thayer's Note: To give it its modern name, the small island of Ventotene, S of Rome by some distance in the Gulf of Gaeta. For a map and 11 informative photos of both the island and the imperial villa, see
		<A HREF="
http://www.romaeterna.org/deambulo/pandataria1/
		"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,2,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
these 2 pages at Roma Aeterna</A>.
	</DIV>


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note81" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref81
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">81</A>
Planasia.

	<DIV CLASS="mynote">
		<P CLASS="b0 a0 justify">
Thayer's Note: The modern island of Pianosa, off Tuscany. For maps, history, and photos, including of some Roman remains, see
		<A HREF="
https://www.associazionepianosa.it/storia/pianosaromani.asp
		"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,2,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Pianosa.Net</A>.
	</DIV>


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note82" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref82
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">82</A>
<I>Iliad</I> 3.40, where the line is addressed by Hector to Paris, with the verbs in the second person.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note83" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref83
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">83</A>
See
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#47
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,5,WIDTH,140)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
chap. xlvii, at the beginning</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note84" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref84
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">84</A>
As well as Salvidienus.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note85" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref85
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">85</A>
That is, while a private citizen could quarrel and make


<A ID="p225x"></A><SPAN CLASS="pagenum">(p225)</SPAN>up with his friends, the emperor's position made his anger fatal.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note86" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref86
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">86</A>
That is to say, holding the highest place in the <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">ordo</SPAN> (<SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">senatorius</SPAN>, <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">equestris</SPAN>, <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">plebeius</SPAN>) of which he was a member.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note87" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref87
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">87</A>
<I>Cf.</I> <A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#56
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,5,WIDTH,140)"
onMouseOut="nd();">chap. lvi.1 and the note</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note88" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref88
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">88</A>
A double word-play on <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">orbem</SPAN>, "round drum" and "world," and <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">temperat</SPAN>, "beats" and "sways."


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note89" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref89
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">89</A>
Probably referring to Livia.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note90" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref90
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">90</A>
The <SPAN CLASS="archaic">choragus</SPAN> at Athens had charge of the costuming and stage setting of plays. Hence the meaning is here "when they had found someone to make them up."


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note91" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref91
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">91</A>
According to some, the choragus; others regard it as the name of a place.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note92" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref92
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">92</A>
<SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">Corinthiarius</SPAN>: coined in jest on the analogy of
		<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/secondary/SMIGRA*/Argentarii.html
		"TARGET="princeps"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Smith1,WIDTH,SmithWidth1)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
argentarius</A>; used in inscr. of slaves in charge of the <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">vasa Corinthia</SPAN>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note93" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref93
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">93</A>
<I>Cf.</I> <A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#41
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,5,WIDTH,140)"
onMouseOut="nd();">chap. xli.1</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note94" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref94
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">94</A>
When the freedom of the Saturnalia justified it.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note95" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref95
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">95</A>
When only aces appeared, the throw was called <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">canis</SPAN>; when all the dice turned up different numbers, <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">Venus</SPAN>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note96" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref96
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">96</A>
The "five-day" festival of Minerva, March 20‑25.

	<DIV CLASS="mynoteWide">
		<P CLASS="b0 a0 justify">
Thayer's Note: For comprehensive details and sources, see the article
		<A HREF="
