E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref109
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">109</A>
<SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">Lucubratoriam</SPAN>, "for working by lamp-light."


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note110" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref110
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">110</A>
The <SPAN CLASS="whole">so‑called</SPAN> "Roman nose."


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note111" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref111
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">111</A>
Roman measure; <A CLASS="conversion"
onMouseOver="return Ebox('1m70',WIDTH,40)"
onMouseOut="nd();">•</A>a little less than five feet seven inches (5·58) English.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note112" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref112
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">112</A>
Ursa major, Charles's Wain, the Great Dipper.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note113" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref113
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">113</A>
Apparently a form of poultice; some read <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">habenarum</SPAN> and explain as a kind of truss.

	<DIV CLASS="mynote">
		<P CLASS="b0 a0 justify">
Thayer's Note: The reading <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">habenarum</SPAN> makes good sense to me; see the use of <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">habenae</SPAN> for treating fractures in
		<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Celsus/8*.html#10.1d
		"TARGET="Celsus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LPlusE,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Celsus, <SPAN CLASS="small">VIII</SPAN>.10</A>, and note (subsection <SPAN CLASS="small">C</SPAN>) that such a treatment would stretch the bone, a desirable effect in the case of a limp.
	</DIV>


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note114" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref114
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">114</A>
<I>Cf.</I> 	<A HREF="
http://www.thelatinlibrary.com/horace/epist1.shtml
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox('Click here for<BR>Book I of Horace\'s letters'+Lat2+LatSearch+'nam mihi</SPAN>',WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">Hor. <I>Epist.</I> 1.15.2‑3</A>.

	<DIV CLASS="mynoteWide">
		<P CLASS="b0 a0 justify">
Thayer's Note: For medical commentary and further context in ancient medicine, see
		<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Celsus/5/Introduction*.html#medical_flexibility
		"TARGET="Celsus_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,1,WIDTH,165)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Spencer's Introduction to Book V of Celsus</A>.
	</DIV>


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note115" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref115
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">115</A>
<I>Cf.</I> <A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#72.1.3
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,5,WIDTH,140)"
onMouseOut="nd();">chap. lxxii.1, note <SPAN CLASS="superscript">98</SPAN></A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note116" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref116
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">116</A>
<SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">Albulae aquae</SPAN> were the sulphur springs which flow into the Anio between Rome and Tivoli (<SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">Tibur</SPAN>).

	<DIV CLASS="mynoteWide">
		<P CLASS="b0 a0 justify">
Thayer's Note: For further sources, geographical indications, etc., see the article
		<A HREF="
E/Gazetteer/Places/Europe/Italy/Lazio/Roma/Tivoli/Bagni_di_Tivoli/Roman/Britannica_1911*.html
		"TARGET="princeps"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,1,WIDTH,165)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
<SPAN CLASS="smallcaps">Albulae Aquae</SPAN></A>.
	</DIV>


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note117" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref117
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">117</A>
The <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">pila</SPAN> was a small hard ball. Three players stood at the three points of a triangle (whence the game was called <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">trigon</SPAN>) and passed the ball from one to the other. A skilful player used his left hand as well as his right.

	<DIV CLASS="mynote">
		<P CLASS="b0 a0 justify">
Thayer's Note: For comprehensive details and sources and a woodcut, see the article
		<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/secondary/SMIGRA*/Pila.html
		"TARGET="princeps"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Smith1,WIDTH,SmithWidth1)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
<SPAN CLASS="smallcaps">Pila</SPAN>
		</A>
in Smith's <I>Dictionary of Greek and Roman Antiquities</I>.
	</DIV>


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note118" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref118
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">118</A>
The <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">folliculus</SPAN> was a large light ball. The players wore a guard on the right arm, with which they struck the ball, as in the Italian <SPAN CLASS="source">gioco del pallone</SPAN>.

	<DIV CLASS="mynoteWide">
		<P CLASS="b0 a0 justify">
Thayer's Note: For further sources, see the article
		<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/secondary/SMIGRA*/Follis.html
		"TARGET="princeps"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Smith1,WIDTH,SmithWidth1)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
<SPAN CLASS="smallcaps">Follis</SPAN>
		</A>
in Smith's <I>Dictionary of Greek and Roman Antiquities</I>.
	</DIV>


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note119" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref119
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">119</A>
Many games were played with nuts; <I>cf.</I> <A HREF="
http://www.thelatinlibrary.com/horace/serm2.shtml
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox('Click here for<BR>Book 2 of the Sermones of Horace'+Lat2+'<BR>then search for '+BadF+'nucesque'+CloseF+'')"
onMouseOut="nd();">Hor. <I>Serm.</I> 2.3.171</A>,
	<A HREF="
https://www.hs-augsburg.de/~harsch/Chronologia/Lspost01/Martialis/mar_ep05.html
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(EClickHere+'Book 5<BR>of the Epigrams of Martial'+Lat2+LatSearch+'Iam tristis</SPAN>')"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Mart. 5.84</A>, etc.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note120" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref120
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">120</A>
See
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#81.2.2
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,5,WIDTH,140)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
chap. lxxxi at the end</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note121" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref121
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">121</A>
Brutus published a eulogy of Cato in 46 <SPAN CLASS="small">B.C.</SPAN>; <I>cf.</I> <A HREF="
http://www.thelatinlibrary.com/cicero/att12.shtml#21
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinRef2,WIDTH,195)"
