<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note122" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref122
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">122</A>
Evidently two archaizing grammarians of the day.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note123" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref123
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">123</A>
See
<I>De Grammaticis</I>, x, at the end<!--</A>-->.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note124" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref124
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">124</A>
Thus characterized in contrast with the studied simplicity of the Attic school of orators.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note125" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref125
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">125</A>
See Index.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note126" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref126
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">126</A>
<I>Cf.</I> <A HREF="
http://www.thelatinlibrary.com/catullus.shtml#67
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(EClickHere+'Catullus'+Lat2+LatSearch+'languidior</SPAN>')"
onMouseOut="nd();">Catull. 67.21</A>, <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">languidior tenera beta</SPAN>. All these words, which Augustus is said to have used, are colloquialisms or


<A ID="p255x"></A><SPAN CLASS="pagenum">(p255)</SPAN>slang, and the exact form and derivation of many of them are uncertain.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note127" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref127
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">127</A>
Since <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">sumus</SPAN> was originally enclitic, the forms <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">simus, sumus</SPAN> may have represented the sound between <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">u</SPAN> and <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">i</SPAN> in <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">maximus, maxumus</SPAN>, etc. Or <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">simus</SPAN> may have been formed on the analogy of <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">agimus</SPAN> and similar forms.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note128" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref128
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">128</A>
<SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">Domuos</SPAN> is the earlier form of the genitive, with the suffix <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">-os</SPAN><SPAN CLASS="emend">;</SPAN> <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">domus</SPAN> the later, with the suffix <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">-s</SPAN>. There was no form <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">domos</SPAN>, and if Augustus used it, he probably did so on the analogy of <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">domos</SPAN> <SPAN CLASS="emend">—</SPAN> <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">domus</SPAN> in the acc. plur.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note129" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref129
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">129</A>
<I>Cf.</I> <A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Julius*.html#56.6.2
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><I>Jul.</I> lvi.6‑7</A>, and
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Gellius/17*.html#9
	"TARGET="Gellius"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LPlusE,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Aul. Gell. 17.9.1‑5</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note130" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref130
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">130</A>
<SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">Religiones</SPAN> includes both religious belief and regard for omens and portents.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note131" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref131
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">131</A>
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Pliny_the_Elder/2*.html#55
	"TARGET="Pliny"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Pliny,WIDTH,205)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Plin. <I>N. H.</I> ii.55</A>, says that the laurel tree (<I>cf.</I> <A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Tiberius*.html#69
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><I>Tib.</I> lxix</A>) and the seal are never struck by lightning; and also that lightning never goes more than <A CLASS="conversion"
onMouseOver="return Ebox('1m50',WIDTH,40)"
onMouseOut="nd();">•</A>five feet below the ground.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note132" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref132
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">132</A>
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#29.3
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,5,WIDTH,140)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Chap. xxix.3</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note133" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref133
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">133</A>
This is not in accordance with the emperor's character (<I>cf.</I> <A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#57
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,5,WIDTH,140)"
onMouseOut="nd();">chap. lvii</A>), and Suetonius may have confused him with Caligula; see
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Caligula*.html#42.1.2
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
<I>Calig.</I> xlii</A>. Yet there are records of many such acts of humility to propitiate Nemesis; see Casaubon <I>ad loc.</I>


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note134" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref134
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">134</A>
The Roman month was divided into periods of eight days, lettered in the Calendar from <SPAN CLASS="lapis">A</SPAN> to <SPAN CLASS="lapis">H</SPAN>. The last of these, every ninth day (<SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">nundinae</SPAN>) according to the Roman reckoning, was a market day.

	<DIV CLASS="mynote">
		<P CLASS="b0 a0 justify">
Thayer's Note: This is misleading, leaving the impression that the nundinal periods were subdivisions of the month. Like our own weeks, they were not. For comprehensive details and sources, see the article
		<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/secondary/SMIGRA*/Nundinae.html
		"TARGET="princeps"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Smith1,WIDTH,SmithWidth1)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
<SPAN CLASS="smallcaps">Nundinae</SPAN>
		</A>
in Smith's <I>Dictionary of Greek and Roman Antiquities</I>.
	</DIV>


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note135" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref135
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">135</A>
Because of its resemblance to <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">non is</SPAN> (from <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">eo</SPAN>); <I>cf.</I> <A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Cicero/de_Divinatione/2*.html#84
	"TARGET="Cicero_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,1,WIDTH,165)"
onMouseOut="nd();">Cic. <I>de Div.</I> 2.84</A>;<A CLASS="correction"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(CarelessLoeb80+'284284</SPAN>',WIDTH,216)"
onMouseOut="nd();">º</A> or perhaps merely because it contained <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">non</SPAN>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note136" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref136
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">136</A>
Into the Eleusinian mysteries of Ceres.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note137" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref137
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">137</A>
The decree was not complete until this was done; <I>cf.</I> <A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Julius*.html#28.3
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><I>Jul.</I> xxviii.3</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note138" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref138
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">138</A>
<I>i.e.</I> "Discourses about the Gods." Aristotle wrote a work with the same title.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note139" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref139
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">139</A>
The <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">genius</SPAN>, or familiar spirit (see
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#note75
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,5,WIDTH,140)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
note on chap. lx</A>), was


<A ID="p265x"></A><SPAN CLASS="pagenum">(p265)</SPAN>often represented by a serpent, and those of husband and wife by two serpents; <I>e.g.</I> in Pompeian frescoes.

	<DIV CLASS="mynote">
		<P CLASS="b0 a0 justify">
Thayer's Note: In Roman art, as far as anyone can tell, serpents as <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">genii</SPAN> appear to be a motif of <SPAN CLASS="whole">Etruscan</SPAN> origin; at any rate, they appear very frequently in very old <SPAN CLASS="whole">Etruscan</SPAN> tombs and sculpture. For a plethora of them, with various explanations, see
		<A HREF="
E/Gazetteer/Places/Europe/Italy/_Periods/Roman/Archaic/Etruscan/_Texts/DENETR*/14.html#sec12
		"TARGET="princeps"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,1,WIDTH,165)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
this long passage
		</A>
of George Dennis's <I>Cities and Cemeteries of Etruria</I>, without neglecting the notes.
	</DIV>


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note140" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref140
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">140</A>
To avoid profanation of the sacred rites.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note141" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref141
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">141</A>
Otherwise unknown; Müller would read <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">Caesarem Drusum</SPAN>. Stahr believes that the reference is to the Eulogy in
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#100.3
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,5,WIDTH,140)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
chap. c.3</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note142" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref142
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">142</A>
Apparently another name for the via Appia; see <SPAN CLASS="small">CIL</SPAN> <SPAN CLASS="smaller">I</SPAN>.1291<!--</A>CIL1-->.

	<DIV CLASS="mynoteWide">
		<P CLASS="b0 a0 justify">
Thayer's Note: For a different and firmer opinion, see the article
		<A HREF="
E/Gazetteer/Places/Europe/Italy/Lazio/Roma/Rome/_Texts/PLATOP*/Via_Campana.html
		"TARGET="princeps"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Platner1,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
<SPAN CLASS="smallcaps">Via Campana</SPAN>
		</A>
in Platner and Ashby's <I>Topographical Dictionary of Ancient Rome</I>.
	</DIV>


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note143" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref143
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">143</A>
Instead of kissing him directly.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note144" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref144
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">144</A>
See
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Julius*.html#note12
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
note on <I>Jul.</I> xv</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note145" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref145
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">145</A>
Marked by the broad purple stripe (<SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">latus clavus</SPAN>). Augustus was not yet a senator, but the privilege of wearing the laticlave was doubtless one of the honours conferred on him by Caesar.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note146" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref146
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">146</A>
Prosper (<SPAN LANG="el" CLASS="Greek">εὐτυχής</SPAN>, "fortunate").


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note147" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref147
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">147</A>
Victor (<SPAN LANG="el" CLASS="Greek">νικῶν</SPAN>).


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note148" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref148
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">148</A>
The <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">lustrum</SPAN> was a sacrifice of purification, made every five years by one of the censors, after the completion of the census, or enumeration of the Roman people. The sacrifice consisted of the <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">suovetaurilia</SPAN>, the offering of a pig, a sheep, and a bull. <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">Lustrum</SPAN> was also applied to the five-year period.

	<DIV CLASS="mynoteWide">
		<P CLASS="b0 a0 justify">
Thayer's Note: For comprehensive details and sources, see the article
		<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/secondary/SMIGRA*/Lustrum.html
		"TARGET="princeps"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Smith1,WIDTH,SmithWidth1)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
<SPAN CLASS="smallcaps">Lustrum</SPAN>
		</A>
in Smith's <I>Dictionary of Greek and Roman Antiquities</I>.
	</DIV>


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note149" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref149
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">149</A>
The
		<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/secondary/SMIGRA*/Pallium.html
		"TARGET="princeps"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Smith1,WIDTH,SmithWidth1)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
pallium
	</A>
was the distinctive dress of the Greeks, as the <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">toga</SPAN> was of the Romans.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note150" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref150
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">150</A>
Greek youths between the ages of eighteen and that of full <SPAN CLASS="whole">citizen</SPAN>&shy;ship, who had regular gymnastic training as a part of their education. The Greek training survived in Capreae, which until recently (see
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#92.2
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,5,WIDTH,140)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
chap. xcii.2</A>) had belonged to Naples.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note151" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref151
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">151</A>
The City of <SPAN CLASS="whole">Do-Nothings</SPAN>. There is no island "near Capreae," and "the neighbouring island of Capreae" is meaningless; if the text is sound, Suetonius is careless, or we must take <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">Capreis</SPAN> as a locative, and regard <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">vicinam</SPAN> as used in a partitive sense like <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">reliquus</SPAN>, <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">primus</SPAN>, etc.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note152" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref152
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">152</A>
<SPAN LANG="el" CLASS="Greek">Κτίστης</SPAN>, the Greek name for the founder of a city or colony.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note153" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref153
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">153</A>
Beneventum;
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#97.3
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,5,WIDTH,140)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
chap. xcvii.3</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note154" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref154
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">154</A>
<I>i.e.</I> open through weakness.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note155" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref155
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">155</A>
Or closed.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note156" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref156
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">156</A>
See
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Claudius*.html#6
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
<I>Claud.</I> vi.1</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note157" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref157
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">157</A>
<SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">Augustus</SPAN> and <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">Augusta</SPAN>, but Tiberius did not assume the title until it was conferred on him by the senate;
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Cassius_Dio/57*.html#2
	"TARGET="Cassius_Dio_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Dio,WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Dio 57.2‑3</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note158" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref158
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">158</A>
See
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Julius*.html#note75
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
note on <I>Jul.</I> lxxxiii.2</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note159" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref159
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">159</A>
See
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#64
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,5,WIDTH,140)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
chap. lxiv.1</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note160" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref160
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">160</A>
Probably those with which he was connected (see
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#40.2
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,5,WIDTH,140)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
chap. xl.2</A>); Lipsius suggested <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">tribulibus</SPAN>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note161" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref161
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">161</A>
That is, on their death; a common euphemism.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note162" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref162
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">162</A>
The original of this inscription is lost, but the greater part of a copy inscribed in Greek and Latin on marble is preserved at Ancyra in Asia Minor and is known as the
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Augustus/Res_Gestae/home.html
	"TARGET="index"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,1,WIDTH,165)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
<I>Monumentum Ancyranum</I></A>.



	<HR CLASS="endnotes"><A ID="endnotes_T"></A>
	<H2>
Thayer's Notes:
	</H2>


	<P CLASS="a0 justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note:Augustus_birthday" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref:Augustus_birthday
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">a</A>
The 23rd of September was Augustus's birthdate in the calendar of the time. It was, however, out of whack with the seasons, as is proved by the frequent statement in ancient authors that his birth sign was Capricorn; some modern writers state that Capricorn was the sign under which he was conceived.
	<P CLASS="i1 b0 a0 justify">
Other evidence as to the actual date of his birthday includes the location of the Ara Pacis in relation to the Obelisk of Augustus
	<A HREF="
E/Gazetteer/Places/Europe/Italy/Lazio/Roma/Rome/_Texts/PLATOP*/Obeliscus_Augusti.html
	"TARGET="princeps"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Platner1,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(see this article)
	</A>
and some of the emperor's coinage, depicting Capricorn, said to be the sign under which he was born (or, according to others — seeking to get around the calendrical difficulties, I think — conceived). A page on this whole question may eventually show up on this site in the fullness of time; this is one of the pages slated to receive a link to it when it does.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note:monuments_at_Nicopolis" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref:monuments_at_Nicopolis
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">b</A>
An excellent paper on Augustus's Nicopolis campsite memorial was once available online at Harvard; with the continued shrinkage of the Web, it has vanished.
<!--
	<A HREF="
http://www.people.fas.harvard.edu/%7eow/Nikopolis.pdf
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,2,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
 -->


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="a0 justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note:Parthina" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref:Parthina
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">c</A>
This note received from Prof. John D. Morgan at the University of Delaware:

<DIV CLASS="prose">
	<P>
There's a foolish error in the Loeb translation of Suetonius, D. Aug. 19.1:

<DIV CLASS="prose">
	<P>
also Asinius Epicadus, a half-breed of Parthian descent, . . .
</DIV>

	<P CLASS="justify">
The corresponding Latin is

<DIV CLASS="Latin prose">
	<P>
item Asini Epicadi ex gente Parthina hybridae, . . .
</DIV>

	<P CLASS="justify">
'<SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">Parthina</SPAN>' means not 'Parthian' but 'of the Parthini', the Illyrian tribe over which Asinius Pollio had celebrated his triumph in 39 <SPAN CLASS="small">B.C.</SPAN>

	<P CLASS="justify">
This is a bad enough mistake that you might want to violate your usual policy of not correcting errors in your sources.
</DIV>

	<P CLASS="justify">
This mistake is probably not one I would have caught on my own — and when putting up translations I don't check them systematically against the original — but Loeb translations are often not the best and do fall into just this kind of foolish error, and the Lewis &amp; Short so defines <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">Parthinus</SPAN> (although it too, like all of us, falls into the occasional error) so I've gratefully incorporated Dr. Morgan's correction.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="a0 justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note:calendar_confusion" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref:calendar_confusion
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">d</A>
It wasn't much of a confusion, nor consequently of a restoration. There had been a communication problem, a translation error between the Greek astronomer who had done the calculations, and the bureaucrats who implemented it: "every fourth year" for the leap years had been understood by the <SPAN CLASS="whole">Latin-speakers</SPAN> as meaning "every third year", since Latin counts inclusively but Greek, as we do today, exclusively. If continued, this would have put the calendar off by a cumulative systematic error of one day every twelve years.
	<P CLASS="i1 b0 a0 justify">
Augustus ordered that the intercalation be set right to one day every fourth year, and that some leap years be skipped to make up for the extra days since 45 <SPAN CLASS="small">B.C.</SPAN> Historians looking for exact dates in Augustus' reign thus need to take into account this slippage and its correction; their task is complicated by our not knowing exactly when the error was caught: see Chris Bennett's very probable solution in
	<A HREF="
http://www.instonebrewer.com/TyndaleSites/Egypt/ptolemies/chron/roman/chron_rom_anl-45.htm
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,2,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
his long, thorough note
	</A>
(on an excellent page about Cleopatra, by the way).


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note:no_crucifixions_when_Augustus_entered_a_city" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref:no_crucifixions_when_Augustus_entered_a_city
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">e</A>
Crucifixions, which appear to have been quite frequent, were carried out along the public roads into the city; the connection, very likely, is not so much one of participating in the prince's mercy, but a cosmetic desire that his eyes should not see these brutal executions. (I cannot avoid being reminded of the firm custom, in the area around Assisi, of not hunting on the feast day of St. Francis.)


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note:quinquennial_games" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref:quinquennial_games
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">f</A>
That is, games held every four years. (<I>Not</I> every five; if this puzzles you, see the article
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/secondary/SMIGRA*/Quinquennalia.html
	"TARGET="princeps"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Smith1,WIDTH,SmithWidth1)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
<SPAN CLASS="smallcaps">Quinquennalia</SPAN>
	</A>
in Smith's <I>Dictionary of Greek and Roman Antiquities</I>, and my note there.)


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note:still_a_virgin" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref:still_a_virgin
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">g</A>
A bit of Loeb prudery: the Latin text reads <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">intactam adhuc et virginem</SPAN>, "untouched until then, and still a virgin."


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note:Astura" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#ref:Astura
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">h</A>
An elegant sea resort in Roman times, mentioned also in
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Tiberius*.html#72.2.2
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Suet. <I>Tib.</I> 72.2</A>, and in
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Lives/Cicero*.html#47
	"TARGET="Plutarch_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EPlusL,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Plut. Cic. 47
	</A>
as the site of a villa of Cicero's to which he fled in his last days and near which he was killed. It was heavily fortified in the 12c and is now the small town of Torre Astura in Latina province: it is about 15 km SE of Anzio (<SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">Antium</SPAN>) by road. See for example
	<A HREF="
http://www.mondimedievali.net/Castelli/Lazio/roma/nettuno.htm
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,2,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
this photo site</A>.



